         <div xml:id="main">
            <head type="incipit">
               <supplied reason="XTF-compatibility">22/8/77. ¶  ¶ I was pleased, dear Mr Bentham, to get the commencing sheets of vol VII ¶  and admire the vigorous continuation of the work as a sound foundation for all future observations, if indeed p...</supplied>
            </head>
            <p rend="number" xml:lang="en">77.08.22</p>
            <p rend="correspondent" xml:lang="en">To George Bentham</p>
            <p rend="location" xml:lang="en">RBG Kew, Kew Correspondence, Australia, Mueller, 1871-81, f. 201.</p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; text-align: end; "
               xml:lang="en">22/8/77.</p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>I was pleased, dear Mr Bentham, to get the commencing sheets of vol VII<note xml:id="ftn1" type="footnote" n="1">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Of Bentham (1863-78).</p>
               </note> and admire the vigorous continuation of the work as a sound foundation for all future observations, if indeed phytographically much should remain to be added.</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Reading your notes on the classification of <name key="Monocotyledoneae">Monocotyledoneae</name>, you must allow me to say, that I merely followed <seg style="">
                  <hi rend="underline">Hasskarl</hi>
               </seg> in uniting <name key="Kyllingia">Kyllingia</name> with <name key="Cyperus">Cyperus</name>;<note xml:id="ftn2" type="footnote" n="2">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Hasskarl (1848), pp. 87-9. Bentham (1863-78), vol. 7, p. 251 wrote ‘F. Mueller proposes to unite [<seg style="font-style: italic; ">Kyllinga</seg>] with <seg style="font-style: italic; ">
                        <name key="Cyperus">Cyperus</name>
                     </seg>, to which it is certainly nearly allied, …’. M in B74 11.01, p. 271 had cited Hasskarl’s unification under <seg style="font-style: italic; ">
                        <name key="Cyperus">Cyperus</name> monocephalus.</seg>
                  </p>
               </note>
               <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>hence I cannot <seg style="">
                  <hi rend="underline">a priore</hi>
               </seg>
               <note xml:id="ftn3" type="footnote" n="3">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <seg style="">
                        <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>a priori?</seg>
                  </p>
               </note> be held responsible for the union. You may have discovered more valid characteristics than were known before, to circumscribe <name key="Kyllingia">Kyllingia</name>. You are also not just to me in regard to my interpretation of the floral parts of <name key="Gramineae">Gramineae</name>;<note xml:id="ftn4" type="footnote" n="4">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Bentham had considered the terminology for the flower parts of the grasses in a lecture at the Linnean Society in November 1876, and said </p>
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 9pt; margin-left: 0.4929in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: 0in; "
                     xml:lang="en">In the large familiar order of <name key="Gramineae">Gramineae</name> … the terminology adopted by botanists has been very unsettled, and repeatedly modified, since Linnaeus first endeavoured to assimilate the spikelet to a flower with its calyx and corolla. For these terms Jussieu substituted those of glume and calyx; and the latter name appears to be still retained by Baron F. von Mueller and a few others, notwithstanding that the absence of all homology between the so-called sepals in Grasses and those of perfect flowers has been so repeatedly demonstrated. (Bentham (1877), p. 513).</p>
               </note> for </p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>1, I did apply only to the inner glumes (glumellas) the term sepals, always distinguishing the outer glumes as bracts, thinking that the two glumellae represented each a solitary remnant of a sepaline whorl.</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>2, This view I found to be erroneous, after I more closely investigated the <name key="Cyperaceae">Cyperaceae</name>; hence I corrected already in <seg style="">
                  <hi rend="underline">1874</hi>
               </seg> my views by a note at 282 of vol. VIII of the fragmenta.<note xml:id="ftn5" type="footnote" n="5">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>B74.13.01, under <seg style="font-style: italic; ">Stipa aristiglumis.</seg>
                  </p>
               </note> In justice to myself this might have been also mentioned, for as your passage runs it would appear, that I regarded <seg style="">
                  <hi rend="underline">all glumes still as sepals</hi>
               </seg> up to the present date. </p>
            <p rend="valediction"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; margin-left: 1.75in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: 0in; "
               xml:lang="en">Regardfully yrs</p>
            <p rend="valediction"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; margin-left: 1.75in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: 0in; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Ferd. von Mueller</p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <name key="Carpha">Carpha</name> was united by <seg style="">
                  <hi rend="underline">Endlicher</hi>
               </seg> (gen. pl.)<note xml:id="ftn6" type="footnote" n="6">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Endlicher (1836-40), p. 113.</p>
               </note> not by me with <name key="Chaetospora">Chaetospora</name>; this I distinctly stated in the fragm.<note xml:id="ftn7" type="footnote" n="7">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>B75.02.01, p. 39, under <seg style="font-style: italic; ">
                        <name key="Chaetospora">Chaetospora</name> alpina.</seg>
                  </p>
               </note>
            </p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
